Suspicious IP Investigation — 185.220.101.45

What is this project?
This project simulates a real investigation that a SOC Analyst would perform on a suspicious IP address. I came across IP 185.220.101.45 while researching threat activity online and decided to investigate it.

Tools Used
Before starting this project, I did some research to find out which tools SOC analysts commonly use to investigate suspicious IP addresses. I came across several options, but I decided to go with AbuseIPDB and VirusTotal because they were the most straightforward to understand at my current level of study.

AbuseIPDBA community database where security professionals report malicious IPs. It gives a quick abuse score and history — one of the first tools analysts check when an IP looks suspicious.
and
VirusTotalChecks the IP against 90+ security vendors at the same time. Instead of trusting one source, you get a consensus from dozens of companies in seconds.

 What I Found
Using both tools I was able to put together a clear picture of what this IP was doing:

AbuseIPDB returned a 96% abuse confidence score with over 6,500 reports from nearly 600 different sources going back to December 2020

VirusTotal had 18 out of 94 security vendors flagging it as malicious, with active brute-force attacks confirmed as recently as 4 days before the investigation

The IP is a Tor exit node  meaning it is used to hide the identity of whoever is behind the attacks, making it very hard to trace

Attack types observed included: Brute-Force, SQL Injection, Web App Attacks, DDoS, and Port Scanning

The IP was still actively reporting malicious activity as of April 2026

About the Report Format

For this project I put together an investigation report documenting all findings. The layout and format were built with the help of AI as a learning exercise.

I do want to note that in a real SOC environment, every company has its own way of writing reports their own templates, formats, and internal standards i guess. The report I created here is meant to simulate that experience and practice the documentation side of the job, not to represent one universal standard.

